{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6e995500-f497-4c3d-a7f2-ff6e39db1de6","content":"**MSTest.Sdk 4.x dropped the VSTest bridge by default.** Your project now only exposes tests through `Microsoft.Testing.Platform`, so `vstest.console.exe` sees nothing.\n\nYou have two options:\n\n### Option 1 — Re-enable the VSTest bridge (quick fix)\n\nAdd this to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatformVSTestBridge>true</EnableMicrosoftTestingPlatformVSTestBridge>\n```\n\n### Option 2 — Migrate your CI off vstest.console (recommended)\n\nUse `dotnet test` or run the test executable directly, since it's now a native Microsoft.Testing.Platform app:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test TestProject.csproj\n# or\n./bin/Debug/net8.0/TestProject --list-tests\n```\n\nOption 2 is the forward-looking path — the VSTest bridge is a compatibility shim that may be removed in a future release.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"75a01152-4c6d-4ce5-bb74-f327d7ed968e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a known breaking change in MSTest.Sdk. Starting with MSTest.Sdk 3.x, the SDK used Microsoft.Testing.Platform but still supported VSTest by default. In MSTest.Sdk 4.0+, the VSTest compatibility layer was removed by default. This means `vstest.console` can no longer discover or run tests unless you explicitly opt back in.\n\nThe key change: **MSTest.Sdk 4.x no longer enables the VSTest bridge/adapter by default**. The project now only supports `Microsoft.Testing.Platform` runner natively. If your CI uses `vstest.console.exe` (or `dotnet test` with the VSTest runner), tests won't be discovered.\n\n\nTo fix this, I can either recommend switching to `dotnet test` with the native Microsoft.Testing.Platform support, or adding a project property to re-enable the VSTest compatibility layer for backward compatibility.","outputTokens":513,"requestId":"E3CE:352E3B:C8FACC:E44518:6A053F82"},"id":"43a4202d-ca2e-4597-af80-d504f7eb383a","timestamp":"2026-05-14T03:20:46.